  "prompt": "How much do furniture salesmen make?",
  "response": "Furniture salesmen's earnings vary based on several factors, including base salary, commission structures, experience, location, and the type of store. Here's a breakdown:\n\n1. **Base Salary**: Typically ranges from **$25,000 to $35,000 annually** for entry-level roles. More experienced salespeople or those in high-end stores may earn higher bases.  \n2. **Commissions**: Often the largest variable, adding **$10,000 to $50,000+** annually. Commission rates range from **3% to 10%+** of sales, depending on product margins and store policies.  \n3. **Total Earnings**: Combined, total compensation usually falls between **$35,000 and $85,000+ per year**. Top performers in luxury or high-volume stores can exceed $100,000 with bonuses and incentives.  \n\n**Key Factors Influencing Earnings**:  \n- **Location**: Urban areas (e.g., New York, San Francisco) often pay more due to higher living costs and customer spending.  \n- **Store Type**: High-end furniture retailers or design-focused stores offer higher commissions on expensive items.  \n- **Experience**: Seasoned salespeople negotiate better terms and build clientele, boosting repeat sales.  \n- **Economic Conditions**: Housing market trends and consumer spending habits directly impact sales volume.  \n\n**Additional Considerations**:  \n- **Part-Time Roles**: May be commission-only or hourly, with less stability.  \n- **Benefits**: Some employers offer health insurance, retirement plans, or employee discounts.  \n- **Online Competition**: While e-commerce grows, in-store sales roles remain focused on personalized service and big-ticket items.  \n\n**Sources**: Data from Payscale, Glassdoor, and BLS (retail salesworker averages). Note that exact figures vary widely, but proactive salespeople in thriving markets can achieve significant earnings.",
